text:
It all started with my love for science. When I was a kid, my parents let me discover it by myself and provided me the material necessary to fully enjoy this wonderful world. It may seems dangerous to let a kid build things with tools like a saw or handling chemicals that could be harmful however, it is by taking risks that we can move forward. Of course, I got injured. I remember cutting my finger with a knife while cutting cardboard and my mother was really scared but after that, it never happened again. Errors make us better.
From experimenting with my hands in the real world, I quickly got involved with technology. I started by dismantling computer rather than using them but after a while, I got really hooked to my machine and its screen. Everything I know today, I learned it by myself. And it is not very different than experimenting with chemicals, you will do mistakes. And for me, it was installing malwares because I did not knew they were harmful, or doing things that could be illegal.
In high school, when we had to make a choice about our future, at first, I wanted to become a chemistry engineer. My grades were great and I really enjoyed experimenting. Even if I liked using a computer, I never imagined a career in computer science.
Then comes the summer vacations. It was hot and I did not knew how to spend my days. I do not exactly know how I started it but I followed a online course about web development : The web developer boot camp by Colt Steel. I began without knowledge of how a web application works but this fourty-ish hours of video gave me a very good understanding of complexe modern websites.
Right after finishing the course, I wanted to apply the knowledge I had gain. My mother, a teacher, always wanted tools to automate some tasks in her class. That is how I began coding as a hobby.
I quickly felt limited with the basic knowledge I had, I was eager to learn more and more, but know, I knew what to look for and where I could find the information I need. Luckily for me, I have a quite good understanding of English. This allows me to have access to almost the entire knowledge base of the internet.
After that, the gear was engaged and my future took the path of computer science and I am really happy of who I am today.
